To serve these purposes, the test rig needs to be improved, in particular:


an actuator power that makes quicker strokes possible;

an incursion cell with a higher rigidity in the normal direction, to impose more severe normal seal penetration and blade loading;

a cylinder’s motorisation that allows testing rotation speeds of up to 100 m/s, and also, that guaranties a constant rotation for surface profile measurement at low speed before and after testing;

a contact thermocouple, welded as close as possible to the blade tip to capture temperature rises during blade/seal rubs; and

inductive components for heating the interaction zone at in-service temperatures.
Another required step is testing and modelling the mechanical and tribological behaviour of the abradable seal material behaviour at high temperatures and strain rates. Modelling the incursion cell will allow to extract the different components of the measured blade/seal interaction force, characterise the seal behaviour in the appropriate loading type and strain rate range.
